 the ratio by the remaining capacity.\n4. Add log of the remaining capacity to the ratio.\n5. Use tan of the difference between bin size and item.\n6. Use arcsin of the ratio of item to bin size.\n7. Use arccos of the remaining capacity.\n8. Use sqrt of the ratio of remaining capacity.\n9. Use log of the difference between bin size and item.\n10. Use log10 of the ratio of item to remaining capacity.\n\nThese are just examples and not the actual functions to implement.\n\n### Conclusion:\nEach function must be unique in the way it combines the allowed operations to compute the priority score.\n\n### Start Implementing:\nNow, think of 10 unique ways to combine the allowed operations to compute the priority score for each bin based on the item and the bin's current state.\n\nEach function should return an array of the same size as bins, with each element being the priority score.\n\n### Considerations:\n- The priority score can be any positive or negative value, but higher scores should indicate higher priority.\n- The functions should be as diverse as possible in their operations to ensure uniqueness.\n- Avoid using the same sequence of operations in multiple functions.\n\n### Final Note:\nEach function must be a valid Python function that can be run with the given signature.\n\n### Example Code:\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    ratio = remaining / bins\n    return np.exp(ratio) * np.cos(remaining)\n\nThis is a valid function, but it's just an example.\n\n### Now, Generate 10 Unique Implementations:\n\nNow, I'll try to come up with 10 unique functions, each using a different combination of the allowed operations.\n\nFunction 1:\nUse the ratio of remaining capacity to bin size and apply an exponential function. Also, add the logarithm of the remaining capacity.\n\nFunction 2:\nCompute the difference between bin size and item, apply cosine, and multiply by the logarithm of the bin size.\n\nFunction 3:\nTake the ratio of item to bin size, apply arcsin, then multiply by the square root of the remaining capacity.\n\nFunction 4:\nCompute the ratio of remaining capacity to bin size, apply tan, then multiply by the logarithm of the item.\n\nFunction 5:\nTake the difference between bin size and item, apply arccos, then multiply by the square root of the ratio of item to bin size.\n\nFunction 6:\nUse the ratio of remaining capacity to bin size, apply exp, then add the arcsin of the ratio of item to bin size.\n\nFunction 7:\nCompute the ratio of item to bin size, apply arctan, then multiply by the logarithm of the remaining capacity.\n\nFunction 8:\nTake the ratio of item to bin size, apply sin, then multiply by the square root of the difference between bin size and item.\n\nFunction 9:\nUse the difference between bin size and item, apply exp, then multiply by the arccos of the ratio of item to bin size.\n\nFunction 10:\nCompute the ratio of remaining capacity to bin size, apply log10, then add the square root of the difference between bin size and item.\n\nWait, but I need to make sure each function is unique in terms of the operations and functions used. Also, I should ensure that each function is correctly combining the allowed operations without repeating the same sequence.\n\nNow, I'll try to write each function step by step, ensuring that each uses a unique combination of operations and functions.\n\nLet me start drafting each function.\n\nFunction 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    ratio = remaining / bins\n    log_remaining = np.log(remaining)\n    return np.exp(ratio) + log_remaining\n\nWait, but this uses addition. Maybe I can combine in a different way.\n\nAlternatively:\n\nFunction 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    ratio = remaining / bins\n    return np.exp(ratio) * np.log(remaining + 1)  # Adding 1 to avoid log(0)\n\nWait, but that's using exp and log. Maybe another function can use log2 instead.\n\nAlternatively, let's think differently. Maybe for Function 1, use the ratio of remaining to bin size, apply exp, and multiply by the log of the remaining capacity.\n\nFunction 1:\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    ratio = remaining / bins\n    return np.exp(ratio) * np.log(remaining + 1e-9)  # Avoid log(0)\n\nFunction 2:\nUse the difference between bin size and item, apply cosine, and multiply by the logarithm of the bin size.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    diff = bins - item\n    log_bins = np.log(bins)\n    return np.cos(diff) * log_bins\n\nFunction 3:\nTake the ratio of item to bin size, apply arcsin, then multiply by the square root of the remaining capacity.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    ratio_item_bin = item / bins\n    arcsin_ratio = np.arcsin(ratio_item_bin)\n    remaining = bins - item\n    sqrt_remaining = np.sqrt(remaining)\n    return arcsin_ratio * sqrt_remaining\n\nFunction 4:\nCompute the ratio of remaining capacity to bin size, apply tan, then multiply by the logarithm of the item.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    remaining = bins - item\n    ratio = remaining / bins\n    log_item = np.log(item)\n    return np.tan(ratio) * log_item\n\nFunction 5:\nTake the difference between bin size and item, apply arccos, then multiply by the square root of the ratio of item to bin size.\n\ndef priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    diff = bins - item\n    ratio_item_bin = item / bins\n    sqrt_ratio = np.sqrt(ratio_item_bin)\n    return np.arccos(diff / bins) * sqrt_ratio\n", 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return np.exp(item / bins) * np.mean(bins)\n', 'def priority(item: float, bins: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    return (item * bins) * np.exp(item - bins) + bins ** 2\n', 'def priority(